        " would lose their property and be condemned to death and that no pagan temples, which had previously been closed, could be reopened. In order to ensure his law was implemented, he set a penalty of  of gold for any judge, governor, or official who did not enforce the law.       When Marcian became emperor, he was influenced by Flavius Zeno, Pulcheria, and Aspar. Flavius Zeno died soon after Marcian ascended the throne, possibly as early as the end of 42 and Pulcheria died in July 42 leaving Aspar as the only major influence in the court of the Eastern Roman Empire. This influence was enhanced by the promotion of his son ": null
